  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_81722480" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/81722480" />
    <a title="Chloe" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/772594-chloe"><img alt="Chloe" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1424620419p2/772594.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/81722480?book_show_action=true">Dec 21, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chloe" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chloe" href="/user/show/772594-chloe">Chloe</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/772594-chloe?shelf=lovely-things">lovely-things</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/772594-chloe?shelf=english-lit">english-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/772594-chloe?shelf=children-s-and-young-adult">children-s-and-young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/772594-chloe?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer81722480" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8312789276888795442">I’m not sure if any other writer quite captures the lyrical simplicity and self-seriousness of a child like A.A. Milne. His use of language is beyond that which most “adult” writers possess, utilizing sparse, elegant verse and paying close attention to the subtle nuances of sound. His subjects are perfect, as well! He clearly remembered being and child and was sympathetic to children. He did not don a pair of rose-colored glasses or talk down to his little readers, but rather he expressed all of</span>
  <span id="freeText8312789276888795442" style="display:none">I’m not sure if any other writer quite captures the lyrical simplicity and self-seriousness of a child like A.A. Milne. His use of language is beyond that which most “adult” writers possess, utilizing sparse, elegant verse and paying close attention to the subtle nuances of sound. His subjects are perfect, as well! He clearly remembered being and child and was sympathetic to children. He did not don a pair of rose-colored glasses or talk down to his little readers, but rather he expressed all of the delicate thoughts and feelings of children themselves. The sense of awe, almost Chestertonian, matches the preoccupation of children with small things, things that seem unimportant to anyone but artists, poets, philosophers and the very young (and God). His ability to craft something as complex as a child’s meditations of self-awareness into something simple enough for a child to read and understand reminds me of Williams Carlos Williams, and yet at face value it’s still a charming book for children. <br />I adored A.A. Milne as a child, and I can still enjoy all of his works today! I will certainly read his children’s books to my kids, if I ever have any. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8312789276888795442" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

